History: -year-old with hypoxemic respiratory failure, assess for interval progression. Comparison is to at 2:15. A portable AP chest film dated at 4 am. Is submitted.
Impression: Right internal jugular introducer catheter has its tip in the cavoatrial junction. Endotracheal tube has its tip approximately 6 cm above the carina. Nasogastric tube is seen coursing below the diaphragm with the tip not identified. A right subclavian PICC line has its tip at least to level of the mid superior vena cava, unchanged. Bilateral diffuse airspace process appears unchanged with the exception of loculated fluid within the horizontal fissure. These findings may reflect moderate-to-severe pulmonary edema, though bilateral infectious process cannot be entirely excluded. The right costophrenic angle is not entirely included on the current examination. Overall, cardiac and mediastinal contours are stable. No pneumothorax.
